uring the Revolutionary and Napoleonic Wars -- tChapter 13 Stalin’s Trap: The Katyn Forest Massacre between Propaganda and Taboo -- tChapter 14 The Great Secret: Sites of Mass Killings in Stalinist Russia -- tChapter 15 Spectacular Atrocities: Making Enemies during the 1965–1966 Massacres in Indonesia -- tChapter 16 A Necessary Salve: The ‘Hue Massacre’ in History and Memory -- tChapter 17 A Battle for Perceptions: Revisiting the Cassinga Controversy in Southern Africa -- tPart IV The Dynamics of Modern Massacre and Mass Killings -- tChapter 18 Method in Their Madness: Understanding the Dynamics of the Italian Massacre of Ethiopian Civilians, February–May 1937 -- tChapter 19 The Algerian War on French Soil: The Paris Massacre of 17 October 1961 -- tChapter 20 Wedding Massacres and the War in Afghanistan -- tSelect Bibliography -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMassacres and mass killings have always marked if not shaped the history of the world and as such are subjects of increasing interest among historians. The premise underlying this collection is that massacres were an integral, if not accepted part (until quite recently) of warfare, and that they were often fundamental to the colonizing process in the early modern and modern worlds. Making a deliberate distinction between ‘massacre’ and ‘genocide’, the editors call for an entirely separate and new subject under the rubric of ‘Massacre Studies’, dealing with mass killings that are not genocidal in intent. This volume offers a reflection on the nature of mass killings and extreme violence across regions and across centuries, and brings together a wide range of approaches and case studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aAtrocitiesxCongressesxHis